x4codes.hlp: iThemba Laboratories, Somerset West, South Africa, Rep.

x4freetext: iThemba LABS, Somerset West,
South Africa (iTL)
iTL, pulsed proton beams with nominal
energies of 80, 120 and 160 MeV produced
quasi-monoenergetic neutron beams via the
p+Be reaction. The proton beam intensities used
ranged between 4 and 10 microA.
Monitor foils, which for these measurements
included Al, Ti, Ni and Au, were placed behind
the primary target(s) and the entire assembly was
wrapped in Al foil for stability.
Plastic scintillators mounted in the beam
at 8 degree were used as neutron fluence monitors
The yields of relatively short-lived
radionuclides that decay by emitting gamma rays
were measured using high purity Ge detectors.

Ti (monitor foil) 0.1         1.5
Fe (target)       0.1                       5 x 5

Ni (target)       0.1                       5 x 5
arget mat.       Purity (%) ppm Mn Typical weight (g)
Ti (monitor foil)  99.6          500         0.74

The relevant parameters used to calculate
the cross sections are in Table 3:
Nuclide Half-life Gamma energy (keV) Branching ratio
The total error in the cross section was
obtained by adding in quadrature, the following
errors:
- the statistical counting errors;
2% for the number of target atoms;
the estimated error in the neutron
fluence, which ranged from 6.4% to 10.4%;
5% for the error in the Ge detector
efficiency.
